# Coding Standards

## Naming Conventions

### Files and Components

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: PascalCase for components with .jsx extension
// Header.jsx, UserDashboard.jsx, JobDetails.jsx
function UserDashboard() { }

// ❌ WRONG: camelCase, kebab-case, or .js extension for JSX files
// userDashboard.jsx, user-dashboard.jsx, Header.js (if contains JSX)
```

### Variables and Functions

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: camelCase for variables and functions
const userName = 'John';
const isSignedIn = true;
const handleSubmit = () => { };
const getUserData = () => { };

// ❌ WRONG: PascalCase for variables (only for components)
const UserName = 'John'; // Wrong - only components use PascalCase
```

### Constants

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
const API_BASE_URL = 'https://api.example.com';
const MAX_FILE_SIZE = 5 * 1024 * 1024; // 5MB
const DEFAULT_USER_TYPE = 'chef';

// ✅ CORRECT: camelCase for const objects
const demoCredentials = {
  employer: ['employer@example.com'],
  chef: ['chef@example.com']
};
```

### CSS Classes

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: kebab-case for CSS classes
<div className="user-dashboard">
  <div className="job-card-header">
    <span className="job-posted-date">Posted 2 days ago</span>
  </div>
</div>

// ❌ WRONG: camelCase in CSS classes
<div className="userDashboard"> // Wrong
```

## Import Organization

### ✅ CORRECT: Import Order

```javascript
// 1. React imports (always first)
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

// 2. React Router imports
import { useNavigate, useLocation, Link, useSearchParams } from 'react-router-dom';

// 3. Third-party library imports
import 'bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css';

// 4. Local component imports (must include .jsx extension)
import Header from './Header.jsx';
import Footer from './Footer.jsx';
import SearchSection from './SearchSection.jsx';

// 5. Asset imports (images, etc.)
import logo from '../assets/images/CHEF_FINDER.png';

// 6. CSS imports (last)
import './ComponentName.css';
```

### ❌ WRONG: Mixed Import Order

```javascript
// Don't mix imports randomly
import './Component.css';
import React from 'react';
import Header from './Header';
import { useState } from 'react';
```

## Code Formatting

### Indentation and Spacing

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: 2 spaces for indentation
function MyComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState(null);

  const handleClick = () => {
    setState('new value');
  };

  return <div className="my-component">Content</div>;
}

// ❌ WRONG: Inconsistent indentation
function MyComponent() {
    const [state, setState] = useState(null);
  const handleClick = () => {
      setState('new value');
  };
}
```

### Semicolons

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use semicolons consistently
const name = 'John';
const handleClick = () => {
  console.log('clicked');
};

// Either use semicolons everywhere or nowhere (project uses them)
```

### Quotes

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use single quotes for JavaScript strings
const name = 'John';
const className = 'my-class';

// ✅ CORRECT: Use double quotes for JSX attributes (when needed)
<div className="my-component">
  <button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</button>
</div>

// ✅ CORRECT: Template literals for dynamic strings
const message = `Hello, ${name}!`;
```

## React Best Practices

### Event Handlers

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: Named handler functions
const handleSubmit = (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  // Submit logic
};

return <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>...</form>;

// ✅ CORRECT: Inline arrow function for simple cases
<button onClick={() => navigate('/jobs')}>Jobs</button>;

// ❌ WRONG: Anonymous function that should be extracted
<button onClick={(e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  console.log('complex logic');
  setState('value');
  navigate('/path');
}}>
  Click
</button>
// Better: Extract to named function
```

### Key Props in Lists

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use unique IDs as keys
{jobs.map(job => (
  <div key={job.id}>
    <h3>{job.title}</h3>
  </div>
))}

// ❌ WRONG: Using index as key (unless list is static)
{jobs.map((job, index) => (
  <div key={index}> // Wrong if items can be reordered
    <h3>{job.title}</h3>
  </div>
))}
```

### Inline Styles vs CSS Classes

```javascript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use CSS classes for static styles
<div className="job-card">
  <h3 className="job-title">{job.title}</h3>
</div>

// ✅ CORRECT: Use inline styles for dynamic values
<div style={{ maxHeight: `${height}px`, color: dynamicColor }}>
  Content
</div>

// ❌ WRONG: Inline styles for static values
<div style={{ color: 'red', padding: '10px', margin: '20px' }}>
  Content // Should be in CSS file
</div>
```

